  <content>
    <title>Resource Management</title>

    <summary>Plan to 70% utilisation (not 100%), map skills to tasks from a YAML roster in git, level resource load using critical-path analysis, and track allocations weekly against actuals. Agents propose reassignments; resource managers and individuals confirm. Rate cards live in a secrets store, not in the repo.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>100% allocation is a planning fiction that ignores meetings, support, ramp time, and unplanned work. Real available time is 60–70% of nominal hours. Planning to full capacity means any unplanned event causes a miss. Resource leveling resolves the over-allocation math but must respect morale — the same person reassigned three times in two months will burn out; the algorithm does not know this.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Multi-team programs sharing scarce specialists (security, ML, SRE, designers) where allocation conflicts cause schedule slips</item>
        <item>Agency / consulting environments billing by utilisation with hard hourly budgets</item>
        <item>Programs spanning external contractors with rate cards and SOW linkage to deliverables</item>
        <item>Capacity planning across quarters when demand forecasts must align with hiring pipelines</item>
        <item>Workforce planning during reorgs where role mapping is non-trivial</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Stable single-team product squad with a tech lead doing capacity by feel — kanban WIP limits are sufficient</item>
        <item>Solopreneurs — calendar blocking covers it; resource matrices waste time</item>
        <item>Pre-PMF startups optimising for learning velocity — 100% of one engineer beats 60% of three</item>
        <item>Fixed-bid contracts where resource visibility is internal-only and not a deliverable</item>
        <item>Pure agile teams with stable sized backlogs — let the team self-organize within a fixed capacity</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="roster-and-allocation">
      <p>Store allocations in git as resources/roster.yaml and resources/allocations.yaml, not in spreadsheets. Git diffs explain why allocations changed; spreadsheets erase history. Allocation decisions are context-dependent; understanding why a decision was made requires the diff, not just the current state.</p>

      <rule>
        <statement>Store allocations in git as resources/roster.yaml and resources/allocations.yaml, not in spreadsheets. Git diffs explain why allocations changed; spreadsheets erase history.</statement>
        <rationale>Allocation decisions are context-dependent; understanding why a decision was made requires the diff, not just the current state.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Plan to 70% utilisation, not 100%. Reserve 30% per person per week for meetings, unplanned support, learning, and context switching. Flag any allocation exceeding 85% as RED immediately.</statement>
        <rationale>100% allocation means any unplanned event — a sick day, an urgent bug, a stakeholder request — causes a miss. 70% is the empirically sustainable peak for knowledge workers.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Rate cards live in 1Password or equivalent secrets store, referenced by ID only in the roster. Never commit monetary rates to the repo.</statement>
        <rationale>Rate cards are commercially sensitive and, in some jurisdictions, legally protected compensation data. Committing them to git creates uncontrolled disclosure risk.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="skill-matrix">
      <p>Skill matrix entries are dated, self-asserted, and peer-endorsed. Refresh quarterly. Agents must read skills only from the roster YAML — never infer skills from job titles. Job titles are unreliable skill proxies.</p>

      <rule>
        <statement>Skill matrix entries are dated, self-asserted, and peer-endorsed. Refresh quarterly. Agents must read skills only from the roster YAML — never infer skills from job titles.</statement>
        <rationale>Job titles are unreliable skill proxies. An agent that assumes "Senior Engineer" knows Kubernetes and assigns them a Kubernetes task without checking the roster creates a skill gap that surfaces at the worst time.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Cross-train pairs for any single point of failure: one person who is the only team member knowing a critical system is a staffing risk. Escalate to the resource manager within one sprint of identifying it.</statement>
        <rationale>SPOF skills create delivery risk that materialises on the one week the critical person is unavailable. Cross-training is the only durable mitigation.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="ramp-time-and-vacation">
      <p>Account for ramp time explicitly: a new joiner is 30–50% productive for 4–8 weeks. Under-counting ramp time is a systematic cause of the first milestone slip. Lock in PTO and public holidays before committing to milestone dates.</p>

      <rule>
        <statement>Account for ramp time explicitly: a new joiner is 30–50% productive for 4–8 weeks. Under-counting ramp time is a systematic cause of the first milestone slip.</statement>
        <rationale>Ramp time is predictable and consistent across roles, yet it is omitted from resource plans in the majority of projects. Treating a new hire as full capacity from day one is a planning error.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Lock in PTO and public holidays before committing to milestone dates. Vacation calendars are inputs to the schedule, not afterthoughts.</statement>
        <rationale>Holiday and vacation conflicts discovered after milestone commitments require scope reduction or timeline extension. Discovery before commitment costs a calendar API call.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="leveling-techniques">
      <p>Resource leveling resolves allocation conflicts. Use peak-trough leveling: move non-critical-path tasks into under-utilised weeks before adding resources or extending the timeline. Cap reassignments per person to two per quarter to avoid morale damage and context-switching overhead.</p>

      <rule>
        <statement>Use peak-trough leveling: move non-critical-path tasks into under-utilised weeks before adding resources or extending the timeline. Analyse the critical path first; do not level critical tasks.</statement>
        <rationale>Adding resources to critical tasks has limited ROI (Brook's Law). Non-critical tasks have schedule float that can absorb leveling moves without impacting the delivery date.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Cap reassignments per person to two per quarter. More frequent reassignments produce context-switching overhead and morale damage that the utilisation math does not capture.</statement>
        <rationale>Resource leveling algorithms optimise utilisation numbers, not morale. A resource who is moved three times in two months is a churn and attrition risk regardless of what the matrix shows.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="contractor-linkage">
      <p>Contractor linkage enforces boundaries between allocation and procurement. Never allocate a contractor beyond the hours in their signed SOW. Timezone overlap matters more than raw hours for collaboration-heavy work.</p>

      <rule>
        <statement>Never allocate a contractor beyond the hours in their signed SOW. Agent must refuse allocation that exceeds the SOW ceiling and flag it to procurement for a change order.</statement>
        <rationale>Over-allocating a contractor without a change order creates an unenforceable claim and a compliance risk if the contractor is classified as a de-facto employee in some jurisdictions.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Timezone overlap matters more than raw hours for collaboration-heavy work. Surface timezone_overlap_hours in skill-matching output; minimum 2 hours of business-hour overlap required for daily collaboration.</statement>
        <rationale>A resource in a non-overlapping timezone can provide async output but not synchronous collaboration. Treating them as equivalent to a co-located resource produces daily coordination failures.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="antipatterns">
      <antipattern>
        <description>Agent over-allocates top performers because they have the highest skill scores.</description>
        <reason>Hard-cap any resource at 85% in the allocation engine. Top performers are also the highest attrition risk when consistently overloaded.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Static resource plans not reconciled against actuals for more than two weeks.</description>
        <reason>Allocation plans go stale in 2–4 weeks. An unreconciled plan produces over-confidence in capacity estimates that do not reflect real availability.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Skill matching by free-text similarity rather than explicit skill keys from roster.yaml.</description>
        <reason>Embedding-based skill matching from job descriptions produces plausible but unverified matches. Only roster.yaml is authoritative; reject any match not grounded in a roster entry.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="privacy">
      <p>Skill matrices and performance ratings are PII and commercially sensitive. Require a DPA before sending roster data to a third-party model. Never auto-publish utilisation reports outside the resource management owner. In many EU jurisdictions, skill assessments and performance data require explicit legal basis for processing.</p>

      <rule>
        <statement>Skill matrices and performance ratings are PII and commercially sensitive. Require a DPA before sending roster data to a third-party model. Never auto-publish utilisation reports outside the resource management owner.</statement>
        <rationale>In many EU jurisdictions, skill assessments and performance data require explicit legal basis for processing. Uncontrolled publication violates GDPR and damages employee trust.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="agentic-workflow">
      <p>Resources are a typed resources/roster.yaml (one entry per named resource: role, skills with levels, hours per week, calendar URL, manager, cost rate, vacation, location/timezone) plus resources/allocations.yaml (resource_id → activity_id → hours per week). A capacity-planning subagent reconciles allocations against schedule and roster, flags overloads, suggests level-loading swaps, and emits a utilization report. A skill-matching subagent reads requirement → suggests candidates from roster with skill-fit scores and current load. Both never auto-assign — they emit recommendations that the resource manager and individuals confirm.</p>

      <p>Recommended subagents: faion-sdd-executor-agent drives capacity planning as SDD tasks (TASK_roster_baseline, TASK_quarterly_capacity, TASK_skill_matrix_refresh). Custom capacity-planner-agent (sonnet) reads schedule + roster + allocations; emits weekly utilization with overload/underload flags and suggested rebalancing. Custom skill-matcher-agent (sonnet) given activity skill requirements + roster, ranks candidates by fit, current load, cost, location/timezone overlap. Custom vacation-impact-agent (sonnet) computes critical-path impact of planned PTO; flags conflicts before approval. Custom contractor-onboarding-agent (haiku) drives the procurement → onboarding → access provisioning checklist for new contractors. Custom attrition-risk-agent (opus) combines tenure, role mobility, sentiment signals (anonymous survey deltas, scope churn) to flag retention risk; output is a 1:1 prompt, not a personnel decision. password-scrubber-agent runs over roster/allocation files; rate cards and skill ratings are sensitive.</p>

      <example type="good" title="Skill-matching prompt">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[You are skill-matcher. Inputs: activity {id, skills_required[{skill, level}],
start, end, hours}, roster.yaml, allocations.yaml.
For each candidate emit STRICT JSON:
{ "resource_id": "...",
  "skill_fit": 0.0-1.0,
  "available_hours": <number>,
  "current_overlap": <hours/wk>,
  "rate": <currency>,
  "tz_overlap_hours": <number>,
  "concerns": ["..."],
  "recommend": "primary|backup|no" }
Rules: do not invent skills. Cap recommendations to top 5.
"primary" requires skill_fit >= 0.8 AND available_hours >= required.]]></code>
      </example>

      <example type="good" title="Capacity-planning prompt">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[Given allocations.yaml + roster.yaml, compute per-resource per-week utilization. Flag any resource at >85% as RED and propose a swap from <70% utilized resources with overlapping skills.]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="cli-tools">
      <p>CLI tools for resource management: git + git log for history of allocation decisions; yq to patch roster/allocations YAML; jq to reduce JSON exports from HRIS / PSA tools; pandas (Python) for capacity math, pivot by week / role / skill; mermaid-cli (mmdc) to render Gantt + resource histogram; holidays (pip) for country-specific public holidays for capacity adjustment; pre-commit to block allocation edits without rationale and manager approval reference; op (1Password CLI) to store rate cards out-of-band.</p>

      <p>Services &amp; apps: Float / Resource Guru / Runn (lightweight resource scheduling; agent-friendly APIs); Forecast / Harvest Forecast (capacity planning + time tracking integration); Mosaic / Saviom / Hub Planner (mid-market PSA with skill matrix support); Mavenlink / Kantata / Replicon (enterprise PSA; deep but slow integration); Workday / Oracle HCM / SAP SuccessFactors (authoritative HCM data; integrate read-only); BambooHR / Personio / HiBob (SMB HRIS; useful for mid-size programs); Lattice / 15Five / Culture Amp (skill / performance signals; use with consent); Jira Plans / Tempo / Advanced Roadmaps (allocation against Jira capacity in engineering orgs); Microsoft Project / Planner / Loop (common in regulated enterprises); Calendly / Google Calendar / MS Calendar (real-time availability; required for calibration).</p>
    </section>

    <section name="best-practices">
      <p>Plan to 70% utilization, not 100%; reserve 30% for meetings, support, learning, and unplanned work. Skill matrix entries are dated and self-asserted with peer endorsement; refresh quarterly. Cross-train pairs for any single point of failure (one person knowing one critical system → escalate to staffing risk). Allocation in git, not spreadsheets — diffs explain "why this changed", spreadsheets erase history. Time-zone overlap matters more than raw hours for collaboration-heavy work; surface tz_overlap_hours in matching. Vacation calendars are inputs to the schedule, not afterthoughts; lock in PTO before milestone commitments. Rate cards live in 1Password / secure store, not in the repo; reference by ID only. Use peak-trough leveling: move non-critical-path work into trough weeks. Track "ramp time" explicitly — a new joiner is 30-50% productive for 4-8 weeks; under-counting ramp creates the next milestone slip. Couple resource decisions to procurement and cost forecasts; a contractor decision affects budget and margin, not just capacity.</p>
    </section>

    <section name="ai-agent-gotchas">
      <p>Agents over-allocate top performers; force a hard cap at 85% utilization in the prompt and refuse plans that exceed it. LLMs invent skills based on title (called "Senior" → assumed expert). Force skill assertions to come from roster.yaml only. Vacation, holidays, and capacity-impacting events (parental leave, on-call rotation) are routinely missed; explicitly inject these into the prompt. Privacy: roster + rate cards are PII / commercially sensitive; require DPA when using third-party LLMs and never auto-publish reports outside the resource-management owner. Agents conflate availability with willingness — the calendar may be open, but the person may be over-asked; HITL needed before assignment. Resource leveling that ignores morale produces "thrash" reassignments; cap reassignments per resource per quarter. Contractor allocation needs procurement linkage; agent must refuse to allocate beyond signed SOW hours. Skill matching by embedding similarity is shallow; require explicit skill keys and levels, not free-text matching. Auto-replan after every change creates churn; batch capacity replans to a weekly cadence. Human-in-the-loop checkpoints (mandatory): adding a new resource, changing an allocation, terminating an engagement, escalating attrition risk, sharing roster outside the immediate program.</p>
    </section>

    <templates>
      <template path="templates/capacity-check.py" purpose="Flags overloaded resources per ISO week from roster + allocations YAML"/>
    </templates>

